fields.title: Staff Subject List
fields.text:
Controls

Upload Email list: Enter a TAB, comma, and/or carriage return-separated list that will be loaded sequentially into the clients.  

Copy Earnings: Copy Student IDs and Earnings to the clipboard in an ESI Recruiter-compatible format.

Anonymize Data: Once the payments have been exported, this will remove the subject names, emails, and student IDs from the dataset.

 

Table

Client #:  Each client is numbered from 1 to 24.

Name: Subject's full name.

Student ID: Subject's student id number.

Email: Email address to send private invitation links to.

Earnings: Earnings in USD up to this point in the experiment.

ID Label: Subject's in-experiment ID that is visible to other subjects.

Shareable Log-In Link: This unique link that can be shared with subjects to log in as this client.

Connected: Connection status of client to the experiment.

Instruction: During the instruction phase, this shows the current instruction status for the subject.

 

Login

Next available connection: Log in as the next available client that has not Connected.  Note that a subject could log in multiple times by opening this link in multiple windows. This link will auto-forward to the Shareable Log-In Link defined above.

Login by client number: Log in as specified client by number.  Replace "[client_number]" in the link with the desired client number ranging from 1 to 24.  Note that subject could log in as any client by changing the client_number. This link will auto-forward to the Shareable Log-In Link defined above.

fields.title: Staff Control
fields.text:
Start Session: Starts the session and the subject screens will switch to the first phase of the experiment.

Show Instructions: Once all subjects have picked an avatar, show the experiment instructions.  If subjects are not picking an avatar, the instructions will show when the Start Session button is pressed.  Instructions can be optionally disabled in the parameters.

Continue Session: Once all subjects have (optionally) completed the instructions, start the experiment.  The instructions will be hidden, and the first period will start.

Start/Stop Timer: Once the experiment is started, press the Start Timer button to begin the clock.  The clock runs inside the connection for the browser tab that pressed the Start Timer button.  If that browser tab is refreshed or loses connection with the server, the clock will stop.  If this happens, press Stop Timer and then Start Timer to resume from the point the clock stopped.  The experiment's progress is stored on the server and will not be lost.

Reset Connection Status: Sets all client connection statuses to "disconnected".  Note that this will not disconnect any connected clients. This only changes the status.  This will re-open all clients to auto connection.

Reset Session:  Remove all data and reset the experiment back to the pre-start state.

Send Invitations:  Send an email to any subjects that have an email defined.  The email will contain their private login link.

fields.title: Staff Parameters General
fields.text:
Number of Periods: Number of periods in session.

Period Length (seconds): Period length in seconds.

Night Length (seconds): Portion of the period that is night.

Break Frequency (periods): Every N periods add an additional break length.

Break Length (seconds): Every N periods add an additional break length.

Show Instructions: Show or skip the instructions phase.

Instruction Set: Name of instruction set to run. Instructions are defined in the admin panel.

Show Survey: Show the survey after the experiment ends.

Prolific Mode: Run software with subjects from the Prolific database.

Interaction Length (seconds): Length of time a forced interaction will last.

Interaction Range (Pixels): Max distance an object can be away from an avatar for an interaction.

Cool Down Length (seconds): After a forced interaction, time an avatar must wait until the next forced interaction.

Starting Health (0-100): Starting health of the avatars.

Health Loss Per Second: Health is lost by avatars each second due to metabolism.

Health Gain Per Sleep Second: Health gained each second while the avatar is asleep at night. No metabolism while sleeping.

Consumption Alpha: (β * Good_11/α + β * Good_2 1/α)α

Consumption Beta: (β * Good_11/α + β * Good_2 1/α)α

Cents Per Second: US cents earned per second times current health.

Allow Attacks: Allow avatars to attach each other at a cost to health.

Attack Cost (Health): Health cost incurred by the attacker.

Attack Damage (Health): Health damage taken by the target.

Sleep Benefit (Health): Health gained per second of sleep.

Allow Stealing: If true, avatars can harvest from fields that do not belong to them.

Enable Hat Exchange: If true, allow avatars to exchange hats.
 
World Width (pixels): World width in pixels.
 
World Height (pixels): World height in pixels.
 
Field Width (pixels): Field width in pixels.
 
Field Height (pixels): World height in pixels.
 
House Width (pixels): House width in pixels.
 
House Height (pixels): House height

Avatar Scale: Shrink avatar.

Avatar Bounding Box Percent: Bounding box around the avatar to allow an interaction.

Avatar Move Speed (pixels per 1/60 second): The number of pixels an avatar moves every 1/60 of a second.
 
Avatar Animation Speed: Speed at which the wheel turns.

Production Effort: Number of productive units available in each field.

Max Patch Harvests per Period: Number of harvests each avatar can make to resource patch each period.

Chat Mode: Limited allows only the selected words through unchanged. The remaining words are scrambled. Numbers and symbols always go through.

Good Mode: Three-good mode uses the third good as a utility multiplier.

Test Mode: Bots will play as subjects.

fields.title: Staff Parameters Players
fields.text:
Label: Name visible to all subjects in session.

Group: The group player is in.    

Avatar Location (X, Y): Starting location of the player's avatar.

House Location (X, Y): Location of the player's house.

Color: Hex color of the player's avatar and house.

Good One: Player's first good.

Good Two: Player's second good.

Good Three: In three-good mode, the player's third good. Leave blank in two-good mode.

Hat: The hat the avatar starts with.

fields.title: Staff Parameters groups
fields.text: Players in the same group can always interact is each other's houses and fields.

fields.title: Staff Parameters Notices
fields.text:
Text: On-screen text.

Start Period: The period the notice will start on.

Start Time: The time when the notice will show.

End Period: The period the notice will stop.

End Time: The time the notice will stop.

fields.title: Staff Parameters Walls
fields.text:
Info: Description of the wall location

Location: X/Y location of the top left corner of the wall.

Width: Width of the wall segment.

Height: Height of the wall segment.

fields.title: Staff Parameters grounds
fields.text:
Info: Description of the ground element.

Location: X/Y location of top left corner.

Width: Width of element in pixels.

Height: Height of element in pixels.

Tint: Colorize the element with a hex color.

Texture: Pre-loaded texture of element.

Rotation: Rotation in degrees of texture.

Scale: Scale of texture.

fields.title: Staff Parameters field_types
fields.text:
Info: Description of field type.

Display Text: Informational text about the field displayed to subjects.

Good One: First good the field produces.

Good Two: Second good the field produces.

Start on Period: In the first period, the field starts production. The field produces nothing until this period.

 Reset Every N Periods: Destroy un-harvested goods every N periods.

Good One Production Standard Period = ρ1 * α1 * Effort1ω1

Good One Bonus Period =  ((ρ1 * α1 * Effort1ω1) - Harvest_Last_Period1) / ρ1

Good Two Production = ρ2 * α2 * Effort2ω2

Good Two Bonus Period =  ((ρ2 * α2 * Effort2ω2) - Harvest_Last_Period2) / ρ2

fields.title: Staff Parameters Barriers
fields.text:
Info: Description of the barrier.

Text: Text displayed to subject on barrier.

Text Rotation: Text rotation in degrees.

Blocked Groups: Groups that the barrier blocks from crossing.

Location: X/Y location of top left corner.

Size: Width and Height of the barrier.

Period On/Off: Period the barrier activates and deactivates.

fields.title: Staff Parameters fields
fields.text:
Player: Owner of the field.

Field Type: Type of Field.

Location (X, Y): X/Y location of the center of the field.

fields.title: Staff Parameters Patches
fields.text:
Info: Description of the resource patch.

Good: The good the resource patch generates.

Location (X,Y): The location of the center of the resource patch.

Shock On Period: The period the patch's levels move to shock levels.

Group: The group to which the patch belongs. Used for testing.

Starting Levels: The patch's levels at the start of the experiment.

Shock Levels: The patch's levels from the shock period onwards.

fields.text:
Info: Description of the hat.

Texture: The texture file name for the hat.

Scale: Not enabled.

fields.text_html:
Welcome

This is an experiment in the economics of decision-making. The instructions are simple, and if you follow them carefully and make good decisions, you can earn a considerable amount of money that will be paid to you privately at the end of the experiment.

In this experiment, your name is #id_label#, and you are represented with the gear-shaped avatar in the center of your screen.

You and the other #player_count-1# people each control an avatar that can harvest goods from resource patches, consume those resources in your home, and interact with other avatars. Those resources will maintain your avatar's health which determines your earnings.

Your house is the one labeled #id_label#. A map in the top left corner of the area below shows where you are. Try navigating the environment now by left-clicking on the screen to locate your house. Do this now.

Continue to the next page of the instructions by pressing the Next   button.

Health

Your earnings in this experiment are based on how healthy you keep your avatar. All avatars in this experiment have a health score displayed above them. This score ranges from 0 to 100.

For each second that passes, you earn this many US cents (¢):

#cents_per_second# x your health score.

Avatars have a metabolism that slowly reduces their health by #health_loss_per_second# points for every second that passes. If your health score reaches zero, you will stop earning money until you raise your score above zero.

Continue to the next page of the instructions by pressing the Next   button.

Resource Patches

Resource patches are located throughout the environment. Each patch displays how many cherries or blueberries are currently available to harvest. The amount available to harvest depends on the number of available rings around the resource.

To harvest from a patch, move your avatar close to one and right-click on it, then press Harvest   to transfer those units to your avatar. Do this now. After you harvest, the outer-most ring around the resource is greyed out, leaving fewer units for another person to harvest. Each time someone harvests from a patch, one ring is removed.

One ring, and only one ring, will grow back each period.

Each patch has a maximum number of rings, which may differ for different patches.

Your avatar can only harvest from one patch each period.

Continue to the next page of the instructions by pressing the Next   button.

Houses

Your house converts any resources it contains into health for your avatar at the end of each period. The amount of health you will gain is displayed at the bottom of your house. Move some of the resources you harvested earlier from your avatar into your house by moving your avatar close to your house and right-clicking on your house. Use the menu to select the desired amount, then press Move  . Do this now. Notice that the amount of health you will receive at the end of the period has increased. (For the purposes of the instructions, we have added extra goods to your house.)

An equal number of cherries and blueberries in your house generates more health points than an unequal number of the same total. For example, if you have 6 cherries  and 6 blueberries  in your house, #healthpoints_6_6# health points will be added to your total. But if you have 2 cherries and 10 blueberries in your house, only #healthpoints_10_2# health points will be added. Additional single units of either resource will always increase the number of health points a house will generate.

You can move resources out of your house by changing the menu to "House -> Avatar". Try moving goods in and out of your house now to see how it affects your health points.

You can move resources into another avatar's house, but you cannot move them out.

Any harvested resources not in a house perish at the end of each period.

Continue to the next page of the instructions by pressing the Next   button.

Sleep

A #night_length#-second night phase occurs at the end of every period. During the night, you can rest your avatar at your house. For every second of sleep your avatar gets, its health will rise by #heath_gain_per_sleep_second#. While your avatar is asleep, it cannot move or interact with the environment. To sleep,  right-click  on your house and press the Sleep   button. Do this now. Avatars can only sleep during the night and will automatically awaken at the start of the next period.

Continue to the next page of the instructions by pressing the Next   button.

Other Avatars

Every participant in this experiment is assigned an avatar. Your avatar can interact with other nearby avatars by right-clicking  on them. Move your avatar close to another avatar and interact with it. The other avatar must be within the circle surrounding your avatar to interact. You can move resources to another avatar like you can move resources to a house.

You can attack another avatar by pressing the Attack  button at the bottom of the avatar interaction menu. Do this now. An attack will reduce the target's health by #attack_damage# points. An attack will also reduce the attacker's health by #attack_cost# points. After an attack, the target and the attacker's avatar are subject to a #cool_down_length#-second cool down where neither avatar can attack.

Each avatar is assigned a hat at the start of the experiment. You can trade hats with other avatars using the Trade Hats   button in the avatar interaction menu. Both parties must agree to the trade. (Hat trading is disabled during the instructions.)

Continue to the next page of the instructions by pressing the Next   button.

Chat

You can chat with other nearby avatars using the chat box at the bottom of your screen. Do this now.

Avatars in other groups do not speak the same language as avatars in your group. This limits the available words you can use to communicate with other groups. It is up to you to discover which words work and which appear in a different language.

You are free to discuss any aspects of the experiment, with the following exceptions: you may not reveal your name, discuss side payments outside the laboratory, or engage in inappropriate language (including such shorthand as ‘WTF’). If you do, you will be excused and forgo your experiment earnings.

Every #break_frequency# periods has a #break_length#-second break phase, where chatting is enabled, but all other interactions are disabled. Metabolism and earnings are paused during the break phase.

Continue to the next page of the instructions by pressing the Next   button.

Conclusion

Many of the interaction menus have a help button  that you can use to reference the instructions during the experiment.

This is the end of the instructions. If you have any questions, please raise your hand, and a monitor will come by to answer them. If you are finished with the instructions, please click the Start   button located in the bottom right of this frame. The instructions will remain on your screen until the experiment begins. We need everyone to click the  Start   button before we can begin the experiment.
